---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import { meta } from '../../data/snapshot';

// Methodology change log — the site-visible record of versions, panel
// changes, and series notices. Entries are appended, never edited; the
// notice for a pending change carries its comment window and effective
// date. Non-material operational changes live in the public data
// repository's log; this page carries what a reader of the series needs.

const entries = [
  {
    date: '2026-07-10',
    tag: 'Notice · pending',
    title: 'Methodology v2.1.0 — panel addition: Lightning AI (effective 2026-07-15)',
    body: [
      `CCIR will add Lightning AI (its own bare-metal rate card, US) to the
       rate panel effective with the 2026-07-15 daily fixing, and the
       methodology version will increment from v2.0.0 to v2.1.0. Lightning AI
       posts guaranteed on-demand and interruptible rates for H100 and B200
       at single-node granularity. Only Lightning AI's own capacity is added:
       capacity the platform re-sells for operators already on the panel is
       excluded, so that each operator holds exactly one panel vote. Voltage
       Park, which has announced a merger with Lightning AI, remains a
       separate panel source while its own rate card remains posted; if
       either card is withdrawn, its series ends rather than being spliced.`,
      `Anticipated effect at announcement: the neocloud (T2) H100 on-demand
       US panel deepens from 11 to 12 sources and the headline statistic
       moves approximately +2% on the announcement-date panel. The realized
       with/without decomposition will be published with the effective
       fixing. No committed-term series is affected, and no prior print is
       restated. Under the Change Management Policy this addition is below
       the material-change threshold; it is announced in advance, with the
       observation window published, as a matter of practice.`,
      `Comments are invited to research@ccir.io through 2026-07-14.`,
    ],
  },
  {
    date: '2026-07-10',
    tag: 'Composition note',
    title: 'July 1–2 panel expansion — eleven sources entered; several cells stepped',
    body: [
      `The 2026-07-01/02 coverage expansion took the collection panel from
       31 to 41 sources (qubrid, sesterce, atlas_cloud, gcore, seeweb,
       upcloud, civo, oblivus on 07-01; ionet, spheron, hyperbolic on
       07-02), and Google Cloud Platform's H100 on-demand US rows began
       flowing in the same deploy window. Published medians stepped where
       the new panelists' price levels entered existing cells — among
       them the neocloud (T2) A100 US on-demand series ($2.70 → $1.81),
       the T2 H200 US series ($5.14 → $4.29), and the hyperscaler (T1)
       H100 US series ($8.44 → $9.15, covered in the 2026-07-03 note
       below, which this entry extends). These steps are composition
       effects — panel deepening — not repricing by any operator;
       readers citing week-over-week changes in the affected series across
       the July 1–2 boundary should treat them accordingly.`,
    ],
  },
  {
    date: '2026-07-03',
    tag: 'Composition note',
    title: 'T1 H100 on-demand US — fourth source enters the panel',
    body: [
      `Google Cloud Platform's H100 on-demand US rows began flowing into the
       panel on 2026-07-02/03, deepening the hyperscaler (T1) H100 US cell
       from three sources to four. The published series stepped from $8.44 to
       $9.15 on 2026-07-03. This is a composition effect — the arrival of a
       fourth source's price level — not a repricing by any operator: no T1
       source changed a posted on-demand rate on those dates. Readers citing
       the T1 H100 US series across that boundary should treat the step
       accordingly.`,
    ],
  },
  {
    date: '2026-04-26',
    tag: 'Version',
    title: 'Methodology v2.0.0 — first public version, effective',
    body: [
      `The v2.0.0 methodology took effect: chip × operator-class × geography
       series grammar, operator-equal weighting, the published headline
       statistic rule, and the panel roster freeze. Prior drafts are archived
       in the methodology repository; every published row from this date
       carries its methodology version.`,
    ],
  },
];
---
<Base
  title="Methodology Change Log · CCIR"
  ogImage="/og/documents.png"
  description="The running record of CCIR methodology versions, panel changes, and series notices — each change announced with its effective date, anticipated effect, and comment window."
  showTape={false}
>
  <section class="wrap top">
    <header class="page-head">
      <div class="kicker">Documents · Change Log · as published {meta.as_of_date}</div>
      <h1>Methodology Change Log</h1>
      <p class="standfirst">
        The running record of changes to what the published series measure:
        methodology versions, panel membership, and composition notes.
        Entries are appended, never edited. Pending changes are announced
        here before they take effect, with the anticipated impact stated and
        a comment window to <a href="mailto:research@ccir.io">research@ccir.io</a>;
        the realized impact is appended at the effective fixing, so each
        change carries both the estimate and the outcome.
        The <a href="/documents/change-management">Change Management Policy</a>
        governs how changes are classified; non-material operational changes
        are logged in the public data repository.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="log">
      {entries.map((e) => (
        <section class="entry">
          <div class="entry-head">
            <span class="entry-date">{e.date}</span>
            <span class="entry-tag">{e.tag}</span>
          </div>
          <h2 class="entry-title">{e.title}</h2>
          {e.body.map((p) => <p class="entry-body">{p}</p>)}
        </section>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <style>
    .top { padding-top: 32px; }
    .page-head { max-width: 80ch; margin-bottom: 26px; }
    .page-head h1 {
      font-family: var(--font-display);
      font-size: var(--fs-hero);
      line-height: var(--lh-display);
      font-weight: var(--weight-display);
      margin: 6px 0 14px;
      letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    }
    .standfirst {
      font-family: var(--font-body);
      font-size: var(--fs-md);
      color: var(--ink);
      line-height: 1.65;
    }
    .log { max-width: 80ch; margin-bottom: 48px; }
    .entry {
      border-top: 1px solid var(--rule);
      padding: 18px 0 10px;
    }
    .entry-head {
      display: flex;
      align-items: baseline;
      gap: 14px;
      margin-bottom: 6px;
    }
    .entry-date {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: var(--fs-sm);
      color: var(--accent);
      font-weight: var(--weight-strong);
    }
    .entry-tag {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: var(--fs-xs);
      color: var(--ink-dim);
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: var(--tracking-eye);
      border: 1px solid var(--rule);
      padding: 1px 8px;
    }
    .entry-title {
      font-family: var(--font-display);
      font-size: var(--fs-xl);
      margin: 0 0 10px;
    }
    .entry-body {
      font-family: var(--font-body);
      font-size: var(--fs-md);
      color: var(--ink);
      line-height: 1.65;
      margin: 0 0 12px;
      max-width: 78ch;
    }
  </style>
</Base>
